column75: Bacon, pecan and chilli crack: Ingredients 200g middle bacon, chopped 1 tbsp maple syrup 1 cup (220g) caster sugar ¬Ω cup (175g) glucose syrup (light corn syrup) ¬Ω cup (125ml) water 100g pecans, toasted, chopped ¬º tsp chilli flakes 1 tbsp thyme leaves 20g butter, at room temperature ¬º tsp fine salt 1 tsp vanilla extract 1 tsp bicarb soda sea salt for sprinkling Method Preheat the oven to 180¬∞C fan forced (356¬∞F). Line a large baking tray with baking paper. Spread bacon out in a single layer and bake for 15 minutes, until browned.  Drizzle over maple syrup and toss bacon to coat.  Cook bacon a further 10 minutes until caramelised and crisp (cooking time will vary depending on how thick your bacon is).  Transfer bacon to a bowl to cool.  Increase oven to 200¬∞C fan forced (392¬∞F). Place a silicon mat or greased foil on the baking tray and return to the oven to heat.  Combine the sugar, glucose and water in a medium saucepan over medium heat.  Stir constantly until the sugar dissolves and the mixture starts to boil.  Continue cooking without stirring, until it reaches 145¬∞C (290¬∞F) on a candy thermometer.  Add the bacon, pecans, chilli flakes and thyme and continue to cook, stirring to mix well, until the mixture reaches 150¬∞C (300¬∞F).  Remove the saucepan from the heat and stir in butter, salt, vanilla, and bicarb soda until the butter melts and the mixture is combined. #cooking #bacon #food #viral

column75: Chilli oil noodles üçú  Ingredients - 280g flour - 160g warm water - A¬†pinch salt - 3 tbsp veg oil - 2 cloves garlic, minced - 2 spring onions finely sliced - 1 tsp chilli flakes - 0.5 tsp cumin seeds - 0.5 tsp Szechuan peppercorns Method 1. Start by making the dough. In a mixing bowl place the flour and salt. Make a well in the centre and pour in the water. 2. Mix until it comes together and you have a shaggy dough. Then turn it out and knead for 6-7 minutes or until you have a smooth dough. 3. Cut into 4 pieces and roll into rounds. 4. Pour 0.5 tsp of oil into a bowl and place the dough ball into it, cover and let rest for 1 hour. 5. When ready, place a large pot of salted water on to boil, and the remainder of the oil in a small pot to heat. 6. Working with one dough ball at a time, flatten it out then make a divot in the centre with a chopstick. Then grab each end and pull to stretch it. Once you have pulled it to around 1 metre, tear the strip in half. 7. Place the pulled noodles into the boiling water and cook for 3-4 minutes. 8. Place the garlic, spring onions, chilli, cumin and Szechuan peppercorns into your bowl. 9. Carefully pour the hot oil over the spices and veg in the bowl before adding in the cooked and drained noodles. Give them a mix and you are good to eat. #cooking #food #noodles #food #asmr #asmrfood #viraltiktok #fyp

column75: Literally gives you perfect memory!! ‚úÖüß†üë©üèΩ‚ÄçüéìüíØ - WHAT IS SQ3R?? ü§ì 1Ô∏è‚É£ SURVEY - glance over the material as a whole, read the summary, make note of the topic, each subheading & section, and any diagrams . 2Ô∏è‚É£ QUESTION - formulate 1 overarching question for each paragraph, and then a bunch of more specific questions for the content of the paragraph or diagrams. Make these questions very specific as this will aid comprehension. These questions will train your mind to actively searching for answers in the next step, thus ENGAGING it during learning. . 3Ô∏è‚É£ READ - read through one section at a time and answer the previously formulated questions. You may need to create new questions if there are gaps. . 4Ô∏è‚É£ RECITE - after each section, recall each question and try to answer them from MEMORY. If you can‚Äôt, look back at the text/your notes and try again. Don‚Äôt move on until you can recite each Q from memory. . 5Ô∏è‚É£ REVIEW - once you have finished all sections, go through the overarching questions for each paragraph, and try to answer them from memory. If you can‚Äôt, look back, refresh your memory and try again. . WHY DOES THIS WORK?? üèÜ By searching for answers to questions, your brain is more likely to deem the content important, understand it, and therefore remember it.  - #studytips #studytechniques #studyhacks #studyhelp #memoryhacks #memorytraining

column75: You CAN do it, I promise ‚úÖüìö here‚Äôs how ‚¨áÔ∏è - During the week, use the following techniques to get all your study done!  1Ô∏è‚É£ TIME-BLOCKING: at the start of each day, plan out exactly what you‚Äôre going to do each day and WHEN. It is especially important to decide when you‚Äôre doing to study during the day and what you‚Äôre doing to study. By assigning a limited amount of time to each task, you‚Äôll give yourself a sense of urgency, helping you complete the task faster. It will also help you find extra time in the day where you could fit in a small task, such as a piece of homework or revision. Finally, it will help you prioritise, and avoid decision fatigue.  For example: 5-6:30am Gym 7-8am Get ready & have breakfast  8-9am Math exam revision  9-12:30pm Classes 12:30-1:30pm Lunch & read English text  Etc. . 2Ô∏è‚É£ Active Study: these are techniques that force you to engage with the content, by doing some sort of physical or mental process. ü§ì  They are much much more effective than passive study and therefore will help you learn MORE in LESS time, meaning that you can limit your study just to during the week & still get the best results.  Examples include: üß† Active Recall (e.g. Flashcards, Blurting, Application Questions) üß† Mind-Maps & Drawing Diagrams  üß† Teaching The Material to Others  üß† Loci Method  üß† Practice Exams  - #studytips #studyhacks #worklifebalance #studywithme #studysmart #studytok

column75: You don‚Äôt need to give up the things you love to get good grades! Here‚Äôs how ‚¨áÔ∏èüìöüß† - THE TECHNIQUES:  1Ô∏è‚É£ Active Recall - this refers to any study technique where you retrieve information when prompted, without reading/looking at your notes. It‚Äôs a great way to memorise information fast!!Examples include: Flashcards, Blurting, Practice Questions üß† . 2Ô∏è‚É£ Spaced Repetition - revise content at regular increasing intervals to remember it better. For example, once when you get home from school, then again that weekend, the next weekend, the next fortnight, the next month etc. You only need to go over your notes briefly each time. Say 15-20mins üìÜ  . 3Ô∏è‚É£ Application - do practice questions (textbook, past year exams, online resources) to learn how to understand APPLY content rather than simply rote learn it. This will help you gain a deep understanding of the content & be able to memorise it FAST ‚úçüèº . 4Ô∏è‚É£ Feynman Technique - learn the content (eg. through active recall above ) then try to teach the subject to someone who is unfamiliar with the topic (e.g. a child, a friend, a family member, stuffed toys if desperate). Being able to do this will help you develop true mastery and understanding of the topic üë©üèº‚Äçüè´ - #studytips #studyhacks #studyspo #studymotivation #studysmart #studytok
